node.text:
The landscape is changing as our #Curiosity #Mars #rover continues to climb Mount Sharp!

Knobbly rocks and rounded hills are starting to appear just as we’re leaving one region of enriched clay materials and entering another with salty minerals called #sulfates. The changes are clues to how this part of the mountain became drier in the ancient past.

Curiosity landed nine years ago on Aug. 5, 2012, to study whether different #Martian environments could have supported microbial life in the planet’s past, when lakes and groundwater existed within Gale Crater.

node.text:
Skywatching tips for August.🤩 

Look up to see a “blue moon,” it'll be the third full Moon out of four this season, where normally each season only has three. This happens every two-and-a-half to three years, or as they say..."once in a blue moon."

You’ll be able to catch the best-known meteor shower of the year, the Perseids, mid-month, peaking on August 12. August is also perhaps the best time this year to enjoy viewing Jupiter and Saturn, as both planets reach opposition. 

"Opposition" is the term for when a planet is on the same side of the solar system as Earth, and directly opposite from the Sun. Around this time, the planet is visible from sunset to sunrise, and reaches its highest point in the sky around midnight. Opposition is also near the time Earth is closest to the planet, or planets in this case, so this is when they tend to look their biggest and brightest.

The scientific heart of the international water-monitoring satellite SWOT, which was assembled in the JPL Spacecraft Assembly Facility, is now in Cannes, France. There, engineers and techs will spend the next year integrating hardware with the rest of the instrument.
 
SWOT is a collaboration between NASA and the French space agency @cnes, with contributions from the @canadianspaceagency and @spacegovuk. This satellite will make global surveys of Earth’s surface water. By measuring its height, researchers can track the volume and location of the finite resource around the world. 
 
It is scheduled to launch in late 2022.

Here’s a closer look at one of the instruments @NASA’s Perseverance Mars rover is using to study the rocks and soil in its pristine environment.
 
Mounted on the "head" of the rover's long-necked mast, SuperCam features a rock-vaporizing laser, camera, and microphone that helps the rover seek organic compounds that could be related to past life on Mars. It can identify the chemical and mineral makeup of targets as small as a pencil point from a distance of more than 20 feet (7 meters).

node.text:
🌄 Cleaner air.
 
A study focused on the early months of the #COVID19 lockdowns found that lower emissions dropped global ozone levels to a place that policymakers thought would take at least 15 years to reach by conventional means, such as regulations. Nitrogen oxide emissions (NOx), which create ozone pollution, decreased 15% globally and as much as 50% locally.
 
Ozone protects us from destructive solar radiation when it’s high above Earth in the stratosphere. But closer to the ground, ozone has other lasting impacts. Ozone at the surface was estimated to cause 365,000 deaths globally in 2019 by damaging the lungs of vulnerable people, such as young children and those who have asthma. It also damages the breathing systems of plants, which is their ability to photosynthesize. That damage reduced plant growth and crop yields.
 
When the world began to go into lockdown, scientists were given a unique opportunity to study how human activity interacts with natural Earth system processes at regional and global levels. A team of researchers focused on the two main oxides of nitrogen: nitrogen oxide and nitrogen dioxide. They charted the chain of events from reduced fossil fuels burning during lockdowns to reduced local NOx emissions and finally to reduced global tropospheric ozone pollution. They found that the stricter lockdowns showed greater reductions in emissions.
 
The total result of the reduced NOx emissions was a 2% drop in global ozone – half the amount that the most aggressive NOx emission controls considered by the Intergovernmental Panel on Climate Change were expected to produce over a 30-year period.
 
Researchers also used measurements of NOx, ozone and other atmospheric gases from five @NASA and @ESA Earth-observing satellites. They fed the observations into four numerical methods of atmospheric chemical reactions and weather, finding that changes in the models’ atmospheres matched the satellite observations and reproduced known increases and decreases in emissions as regions went in and out of lockdowns.

node.text:
✨
 
In June, the after-dark wonders bring us the constellation Scorpius, a Strawberry Moon, Saturn and Jupiter visible in the south at dawn, and a partial solar eclipse visible in the Northeastern U.S. 
 
And for more excitement this month, @NASA's Juno spacecraft is making its next close flyby over Jupiter, and this time it will also make a low-altitude flyby over the planet-sized icy moon Ganymede.

This is the first of several planned flybys of the Jovian moons – including icy Europa and volcanic Io – that Juno will make over the next couple years.
 
More on what to look up to at night: go.nasa.gov/34hp376
 
#Jupiter #Saturn #Moon #Scorpius #skywatching #stargazing #NightSky #astronomy #NASA #JPL

NISAR, a joint @NASA-@ISRO.IN Earth-observing mission, will track the subtle changes in our planet’s surface and spot warning signs of volcanic eruptions.

The satellite will monitor these changes in Earth’s surface over nearly the entire globe. This type of monitoring has not been done before with the high resolution in space and time that NISAR will deliver.

NISAR is set for launch no earlier than 2022.

Listen closely 👂

Do you hear that rhythmic humming? That’s #MarsHelicopter as heard from the SuperCam instrument’s microphone on the #Perseverance rover. It’s the first time a spacecraft on another planet has recorded sounds of a separate spacecraft. This was captured during Ingenuity’s ambitious fourth flight. The rumbling and occasional clipping sounds that can also be heard are the Martian winds. 

Scientists made the audio (recorded in mono) easier to hear by isolating the 84 hertz helicopter blade sound, reducing the frequencies below 80 hertz and above 90 hertz, and increasing the volume of the remaining signal. Some frequencies were clipped to bring out the helicopter’s hum, which is loudest when the helicopter passes through the field of view of the camera.

The landscape is changing as our #Curiosity #Mars #rover continues to climb Mount Sharp!

Knobbly rocks and rounded hills are starting to appear just as we’re leaving one region of enriched clay materials and entering another with salty minerals called #sulfates. The changes are clues to how this part of the mountain became drier in the ancient past.

Curiosity landed nine years ago on Aug. 5, 2012, to study whether different #Martian environments could have supported microbial life in the planet’s past, when lakes and groundwater existed within Gale Crater.

node.text:
Measuring the Milky Way is not easy when Earth is only a tiny dot inside it. 🤏
 
Think of standing in Times Square and trying to draw a map of Manhattan. Thanks to data from @NASA’s now-retired #Spitzer #Space #Telescope and @EuropeanSpaceAgency’s #Gaia mission, astronomers have found a previously unrecognized feature, a “break” in one of its #spiral arms, called the #Sagittarius Arm.
 
A contingent of young stars and star-forming gas clouds is sticking out of one of the Milky Way’s six spiral arms like a splinter poking out from a plank of wood. Stretching some 3,000 light-years, this is the first major structure identified with such a dramatically different orientation relative to the arm.
 
Astronomers have a rough idea of the size and shape of the #MilkyWay’s arms, but much remains unknown. This newly discovered feature offers insight into the large-scale structure of our #galaxy.
 
Swipe 👉
- This artist's concept illustrates the new view of the Milky Way, along with other findings presented at the 212th American Astronomical Society meeting.
- Shown from left are the #Eagle, #Omega, #Triffid, and #Lagoon Nebulae, imaged by the Spitzer Space Telescope. They’re part of a structure within the Sagittarius Arm that’s poking out from the arm at a dramatic angle.
 
#NASA #JPL

node.text:
A dozen for the books! 🚁
 
The #MarsHelicopter’s latest flight success took us to the geological wonder that is the “South Séítah” region. The #Mars chopper climbed to an altitude of 32.8 feet (10 meters) for a total of 169 seconds and flew approximately 1,476 feet (450 meters) roundtrip.
 
After taking images, #Ingenuity returned to the same area from where it took off. This flight was ambitious because flying over this varied terrain carries substantial risk. Ingenuity’s #navigation system – which was originally intended to support a short #TechDemo – works on the assumption that it is flying across flat terrain. Deviations can introduce errors that can lead both to temporary excursions in roll and pitch (tilting back and forth in an oscillating pattern), as well as long-term errors in the #helicopter’s knowledge of its position.
 
When we choose to accept the risks associated with such a flight, it’s because of the correspondingly high rewards. Knowing that Ingenuity can help the #Perseverance rover with its unique aerial footage is all the motivation needed.

Better by the dozen.🚁
 
The #MarsHelicopter is gearing up for Flight 12. It’ll take place no earlier than Aug. 16, and will #scout the geologically intriguing “South Séítah” region for @NASA’s Perseverance #Mars #rover. This #flight will be ambitious, given the varied terrain in the area.
 
In regards to scouting, this flight has the potential to provide impactful results. Thanks to its newly enabled #AutoNav capability, #Perseverance is quickly moving northwest across the southern ridge of Séítah (white path in the image) and will meet #Ingenuity in the coming days.
 
Over the course of the flight, Ingenuity will attempt to capture 10 color images that we hope will help the Perseverance #science team determine which of all the boulders, rocky outcrops and other #geologic features in South Seítah may be worthy of further scrutiny by the rover.

In a new study, @NASA scientists use data from #OSIRISREx, the Deep Space Network, and state-of-the-art computer models to pinpoint #asteroid Bennu’s future orbit and total impact probability with unprecedented detail. The precision-tracking data also gives researchers a better understanding of the object’s movements, reducing uncertainty of its future orbit and improving our ability to predict the orbits of other asteroids.
 
Before leaving #Bennu on May 10, 2021, OSIRIS-REx spent over two hours in close proximity to the asteroid. It gathered information on its size, shape, mass, and composition, while monitoring its spin and orbital trajectory. Based on this #data and modeling, scientists pinpointed Bennu’s future orbit, reducing uncertainty to determine the total impact probability through the year 2300.
 
In 2135, Bennu will make a close approach with #Earth, but it will not be a danger to our planet. Still, scientists must understand the asteroid’s exact trajectory during that encounter in order to predict how Earth’s #gravity will alter Bennu’s path around the Sun – and how it could affect the risk of Earth impact in the future.
 
While the odds of it hitting Earth one day are low, Bennu is still one of the most hazardous asteroids in our #SolarSystem. This study highlights the crucial role that OSIRIS-REx operations played in precisely characterizing Bennu’s orbit.
 
#science #research #NASA #JPL

node.text:
A new resource on rising seas.

@NASA’s Sea Level Change Team created a projection tool that allows you to access extensive #data on future sea level rise from the Intergovernmental Panel on Climate Change. The tool will deliver a detailed report for any chosen location around the globe based on the projections in the IPCC’s Sixth Assessment report that was released Aug. 9.

Along with providing snapshots of future rising sea levels, the tool allows users to focus on the effects of different processes that drive the rise. Those processes include the melting of ice sheets and glaciers and the extent to which #ocean waters shift their circulation patters or expand as they warm, which can affect ocean height.

Observations by the spacecraft’s Jovian Infrared Auroral Mapper (#JIRAM) instrument, which “sees” in #infrared light not visible to the human eye, provide new information on #Ganymede’s #icy shell and the composition of the #ocean of liquid water beneath.

The hardware for Europa Clipper is rapidly taking shape as engineering components and instruments are being prepared for delivery to the JPL Spacecraft Assembly Facility. In workshops and labs across the country and in Europe, teams are crafting the complex pieces that make up the spacecraft.
